of the fourth and fifth fingers","Pain in the shoulder","Loss of sensation in the index finger"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Eclawing of the fourth and fifth fingers\u003C/strong\u003E. Cubital tunnel syndrome involves compression of the ulnar nerve at the elbow, which can lead to weakness and clawing of the fourth and fifth fingers due to impaired innervation of the intrinsic muscles of the hand.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENumbness in the thumb\u003C/strong\u003E - This is more commonly associated with median nerve compression, such as in carpal tunnel syndrome.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWeakness in the biceps\u003C/strong\u003E - This is typically related to issues with the musculocutaneous nerve, not the ulnar nerve.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPain in the shoulder\u003C/strong\u003E - This is not a typical symptom of cubital tunnel syndrome, which affects the elbow and hand.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELoss of sensation in the index finger\u003C/strong\u003E - This is more commonly associated with median nerve issues, not the ulnar nerve.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cubital tunnel syndrome is caused by compression of the ulnar nerve at the elbow.","Symptoms of cubital tunnel syndrome include numbness and tingling in the ring and little fingers, and weakness in the hand.","Clawing of the fourth and fifth fingers can occur due to ulnar nerve dysfunction."],"references":["Anderson D, Woods B, Abubakar T, Koontz C, Li N, Hasoon J, Viswanath O, Kaye AD, Urits I. A Comprehensive Review of Cubital Tunnel Syndrome. Orthop Rev (Pavia). 2022 Sep 15;14(3):38239. doi: 10.52965/001c.38239. PMID: 36128335; PMCID: PMC9476617.","Genova A, Dix O, Saefan A, Thakur M, Hassan A. Carpal Tunnel Syndrome: A Review of Literature. Cureus. 2020 Mar 19;12(3):e7333. doi: 10.7759/cureus.7333. PMID: 32313774; PMCID: PMC7164699","Dincer, F., \u0026 Samut, G. (2014). Physical examination of the hand. In Hand function: A practical guide to assessment (pp. 23-40). New York, NY: Springer New York","Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2018). Textbook of Orthopaedics, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Wojdyla, L., Hughes, T., \u0026 Stelitano, G. (2023). Hand Pathologies. In Textbook of Musculoskeletal Disorders (pp. 675-689). Cham: Springer International Publishing","Mohan, H. (2018). Textbook of pathology. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63809"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18236"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63809","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63809"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-10T20:28:06+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-10T20:29:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10950"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78447"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level